glam::UVec3::dot.documentation: Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::UVec3::dot_into_vec.documentation: Returns a vector where every component is the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::UVec3::element_product.documentation:
Returns the product of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x * self.y * ..`.

glam::UVec3::element_sum.documentation:
Returns the sum of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x + self.y + ..`.

glam::UVec3::extend.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` and the given `w` value.

glam::UVec3::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector from an array.

glam::UVec3::manhattan_distance.documentation:
Computes the [manhattan distance] between two points.
 # Overflow
 This method may overflow if the result is greater than [`u32::MAX`].
 See also [`checked_manhattan_distance`][UVec3::checked_manhattan_distance].
 [manhattan distance]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxicab_geometry

glam::UVec3::max.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the maximum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[max(self.x, rhs.x), max(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::max_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal maximum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `max(x, y, ..)`.

glam::UVec3::max_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first maximum element of `self`.

glam::UVec3::min.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the minimum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[min(x, rhs.x), min(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::min_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal minimum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `min(x, y, ..)`.

glam::UVec3::min_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first minimum element of `self`.

glam::UVec3::saturating_add.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating addition of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_add(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_add(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::saturating_add_signed.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating addition of `self` and signed vector `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_add_signed(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_add_signed(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::saturating_div.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating division of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_div(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_div(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::saturating_mul.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating multiplication of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_mul(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_mul(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::saturating_sub.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating subtraction of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_sub(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_sub(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::select.documentation:
Creates a vector from the elements in `if_true` and `if_false`, selecting which to use
 for each element of `self`.
 A true element in the mask uses the corresponding element from `if_true`, and false
 uses the element from `if_false`.

glam::UVec3::splat.documentation: Creates a vector with all elements set to `v`.

glam::UVec3::truncate.documentation:
Creates a 2D vector from the `x` and `y` elements of `self`, discarding `z`.
 Truncation may also be performed by using [`self.xy()`][crate::swizzles::Vec3Swizzles::xy()].

glam::UVec3::with_x.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `x`.

glam::UVec3::with_y.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `y`.

glam::UVec3::with_z.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `z`.

glam::UVec3::wrapping_add.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping addition of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_add(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_add(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::wrapping_add_signed.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping addition of `self` and signed vector `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_add_signed(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_add_signed(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::wrapping_div.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping division of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_div(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_div(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::wrapping_mul.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping multiplication of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_mul(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_mul(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec3::wrapping_sub.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping subtraction of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_sub(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_sub(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::chebyshev_distance.documentation:
Computes the [chebyshev distance] between two points.
 [chebyshev distance]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chebyshev_distance

glam::UVec4::checked_manhattan_distance.documentation:
Computes the [manhattan distance] between two points.
 This will returns [`None`] if the result is greater than [`u32::MAX`].
 [manhattan distance]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxicab_geometry

glam::UVec4::clamp.documentation:
Component-wise clamping of values, similar to [`u32::clamp`].
 Each element in `min` must be less-or-equal to the corresponding element in `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::UVec4::cmpeq.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `==` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words, this computes `[self.x == rhs.x, self.y == rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::UVec4::cmpge.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x >= rhs.x, self.y >= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::UVec4::cmpgt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x > rhs.x, self.y > rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::UVec4::cmple.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x <= rhs.x, self.y <= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::UVec4::cmplt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x < rhs.x, self.y < rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::UVec4::cmpne.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `!=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x != rhs.x, self.y != rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::UVec4::dot.documentation: Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::UVec4::dot_into_vec.documentation: Returns a vector where every component is the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::UVec4::element_product.documentation:
Returns the product of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x * self.y * ..`.

glam::UVec4::element_sum.documentation:
Returns the sum of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x + self.y + ..`.

glam::UVec4::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector from an array.

glam::UVec4::manhattan_distance.documentation:
Computes the [manhattan distance] between two points.
 # Overflow
 This method may overflow if the result is greater than [`u32::MAX`].
 See also [`checked_manhattan_distance`][UVec4::checked_manhattan_distance].
 [manhattan distance]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxicab_geometry

glam::UVec4::max.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the maximum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[max(self.x, rhs.x), max(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::max_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal maximum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `max(x, y, ..)`.

glam::UVec4::max_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first maximum element of `self`.

glam::UVec4::min.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the minimum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[min(x, rhs.x), min(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::min_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal minimum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `min(x, y, ..)`.

glam::UVec4::min_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first minimum element of `self`.

glam::UVec4::saturating_add.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating addition of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_add(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_add(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::saturating_add_signed.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating addition of `self` and signed vector `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_add_signed(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_add_signed(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::saturating_div.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating division of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_div(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_div(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::saturating_mul.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating multiplication of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_mul(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_mul(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::saturating_sub.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the saturating subtraction of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.saturating_sub(rhs.x), self.y.saturating_sub(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::select.documentation:
Creates a vector from the elements in `if_true` and `if_false`, selecting which to use
 for each element of `self`.
 A true element in the mask uses the corresponding element from `if_true`, and false
 uses the element from `if_false`.

glam::UVec4::splat.documentation: Creates a vector with all elements set to `v`.

glam::UVec4::truncate.documentation:
Creates a 3D vector from the `x`, `y` and `z` elements of `self`, discarding `w`.
 Truncation to [`UVec3`] may also be performed by using [`self.xyz()`][crate::swizzles::Vec4Swizzles::xyz()].

glam::UVec4::with_w.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `w`.

glam::UVec4::with_x.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `x`.

glam::UVec4::with_y.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `y`.

glam::UVec4::with_z.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `z`.

glam::UVec4::wrapping_add.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping addition of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_add(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_add(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::wrapping_add_signed.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping addition of `self` and signed vector `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_add_signed(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_add_signed(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::wrapping_div.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping division of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_div(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_div(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::wrapping_mul.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping multiplication of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_mul(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_mul(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::UVec4::wrapping_sub.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the wrapping subtraction of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.wrapping_sub(rhs.x), self.y.wrapping_sub(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::Vec2::abs.documentation: Returns a vector containing the absolute value of each element of `self`.

glam::Vec2::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs` is
 less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two vectors contain similar elements. It works best when
 comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used depends on
 the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::Vec2::angle_to.documentation:
Returns the angle of rotation (in radians) from `self` to `rhs` in the range `[-, +]`.
 The inputs do not need to be unit vectors however they must be non-zero.

glam::Vec2::ceil.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the smallest integer greater than or equal to a number for
 each element of `self`.

glam::Vec2::clamp.documentation:
Component-wise clamping of values, similar to [`f32::clamp`].
 Each element in `min` must be less-or-equal to the corresponding element in `max`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::clamp_length.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min` and no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max`, or if either `min` or `max` is negative, when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::clamp_length_max.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `max` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::clamp_length_min.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::cmpeq.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `==` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words, this computes `[self.x == rhs.x, self.y == rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec2::cmpge.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x >= rhs.x, self.y >= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec2::cmpgt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x > rhs.x, self.y > rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec2::cmple.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x <= rhs.x, self.y <= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec2::cmplt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x < rhs.x, self.y < rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec2::cmpne.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `!=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x != rhs.x, self.y != rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec2::copysign.documentation: Returns a vector with signs of `rhs` and the magnitudes of `self`.

glam::Vec2::distance.documentation: Computes the Euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::Vec2::distance_squared.documentation: Compute the squared euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::Vec2::div_euclid.documentation: Returns the element-wise quotient of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.

glam::Vec2::dot.documentation: Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::Vec2::dot_into_vec.documentation: Returns a vector where every component is the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::Vec2::element_product.documentation:
Returns the product of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x * self.y * ..`.

glam::Vec2::element_sum.documentation:
Returns the sum of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x + self.y + ..`.

glam::Vec2::exp.documentation:
Returns a vector containing `e^self` (the exponential function) for each element of
 `self`.

glam::Vec2::extend.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` and the given `z` value.

glam::Vec2::floor.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the largest integer less than or equal to a number for each
 element of `self`.

glam::Vec2::fract.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this differs from the GLSL implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::Vec2::fract_gl.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this differs from the Rust implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::Vec2::from_angle.documentation:
Creates a 2D vector containing `[angle.cos(), angle.sin()]`. This can be used in
 conjunction with the [`rotate()`][Self::rotate()] method, e.g.
 `Vec2::from_angle(PI).rotate(Vec2::Y)` will create the vector `[-1, 0]`
 and rotate [`Vec2::Y`] around it returning `-Vec2::Y`.

glam::Vec2::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector from an array.

glam::Vec2::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.  If any element is either
 `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::Vec2::is_finite_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_finite` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_finite(), y.is_finite(), ...]`.

glam::Vec2::is_nan_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_nan` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_nan(), y.is_nan(), ...]`.

glam::Vec2::is_negative_bitmask.documentation:
Returns a bitmask with the lowest 2 bits set to the sign bits from the elements of `self`.
 A negative element results in a `1` bit and a positive element in a `0` bit.  Element `x` goes
 into the first lowest bit, element `y` into the second, etc.
 An element is negative if it has a negative sign, including -0.0, NaNs with negative sign
 bit and negative infinity.

glam::Vec2::is_normalized.documentation:
Returns whether `self` is length `1.0` or not.
 Uses a precision threshold of approximately `1e-4`.

glam::Vec2::length_recip.documentation:
Computes `1.0 / length()`.
 For valid results, `self` must _not_ be of length zero.

glam::Vec2::length_squared.documentation:
Computes the squared length of `self`.
 This is faster than `length()` as it avoids a square root operation.

glam::Vec2::lerp.documentation:
Performs a linear interpolation between `self` and `rhs` based on the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s` is `1.0`, the result
 will be equal to `rhs`. When `s` is outside of range `[0, 1]`, the result is linearly
 extrapolated.

glam::Vec2::max.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the maximum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[max(self.x, rhs.x), max(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics for maxNum and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec2::max_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal maximum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `max(x, y, ..)`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec2::max_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first maximum element of `self`.

glam::Vec2::midpoint.documentation:
Calculates the midpoint between `self` and `rhs`.
 The midpoint is the average of, or halfway point between, two vectors.
 `a.midpoint(b)` should yield the same result as `a.lerp(b, 0.5)`
 while being slightly cheaper to compute.

glam::Vec2::min.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the minimum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[min(x, rhs.x), min(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics for minNum and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec2::min_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal minimum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `min(x, y, ..)`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec2::min_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first minimum element of `self`.

glam::Vec2::move_towards.documentation:
Moves towards `rhs` based on the value `d`.
 When `d` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `d` is equal to
 `self.distance(rhs)`, the result will be equal to `rhs`. Will not go past `rhs`.

glam::Vec2::mul_add.documentation:
Fused multiply-add. Computes `(self * a) + b` element-wise with only one rounding
 error, yielding a more accurate result than an unfused multiply-add.
 Using `mul_add` *may* be more performant than an unfused multiply-add if the target
 architecture has a dedicated fma CPU instruction. However, this is not always true,
 and will be heavily dependant on designing algorithms with specific target hardware in
 mind.

glam::Vec2::normalize.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0.
 For valid results, `self` must be finite and _not_ of length zero, nor very close to zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`] and [`Self::normalize_or_zero()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if the resulting normalized vector is not finite when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::normalize_or.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns a
 fallback value.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be the fallback value.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::Vec2::normalize_or_zero.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns zero.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::Vec2::perp.documentation: Returns a vector that is equal to `self` rotated by 90 degrees.

glam::Vec2::perp_dot.documentation:
The perpendicular dot product of `self` and `rhs`.
 Also known as the wedge product, 2D cross product, and determinant.

glam::Vec2::powf.documentation: Returns a vector containing each element of `self` raised to the power of `n`.

glam::Vec2::project_onto.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is zero length when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::project_onto_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::recip.documentation: Returns a vector containing the reciprocal `1.0/n` of each element of `self`.

glam::Vec2::reflect.documentation:
Returns the reflection vector for a given incident vector `self` and surface normal
 `normal`.
 `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::refract.documentation:
Returns the refraction direction for a given incident vector `self`, surface normal
 `normal` and ratio of indices of refraction, `eta`. When total internal reflection occurs,
 a zero vector will be returned.
 `self` and `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::reject_from.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` has a length of zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::reject_from_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec2::rem_euclid.documentation:
Returns the element-wise remainder of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.
 [Euclidean division]: f32::rem_euclid

glam::Vec2::rotate.documentation:
Returns `rhs` rotated by the angle of `self`. If `self` is normalized,
 then this just rotation. This is what you usually want. Otherwise,
 it will be like a rotation with a multiplication by `self`'s length.
 This can be used in conjunction with the [`from_angle()`][Self::from_angle()] method, e.g.
 `Vec2::from_angle(PI).rotate(Vec2::Y)` will create the vector `[-1, 0]`
 and rotate [`Vec2::Y`] around it returning `-Vec2::Y`.

glam::Vec2::rotate_towards.documentation:
Rotates towards `rhs` up to `max_angle` (in radians).
 When `max_angle` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `max_angle` is equal to
 `self.angle_between(rhs)`, the result will be parallel to `rhs`. If `max_angle` is negative,
 rotates towards the exact opposite of `rhs`. Will not go past the target.

glam::Vec2::round.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the nearest integer to a number for each element of `self`.
 Round half-way cases away from 0.0.

glam::Vec2::select.documentation:
Creates a vector from the elements in `if_true` and `if_false`, selecting which to use
 for each element of `self`.
 A true element in the mask uses the corresponding element from `if_true`, and false
 uses the element from `if_false`.

glam::Vec2::signum.documentation:
Returns a vector with elements representing the sign of `self`.
 - `1.0` if the number is positive, `+0.0` or `INFINITY`
 - `-1.0` if the number is negative, `-0.0` or `NEG_INFINITY`
 - `NAN` if the number is `NAN`

glam::Vec2::splat.documentation: Creates a vector with all elements set to `v`.

glam::Vec2::to_angle.documentation:
Returns the angle (in radians) of this vector in the range `[-, +]`.
 The input does not need to be a unit vector however it must be non-zero.

glam::Vec2::trunc.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the integer part each element of `self`. This means numbers are
 always truncated towards zero.

glam::Vec2::with_x.documentation: Creates a 2D vector from `self` with the given value of `x`.

glam::Vec2::with_y.documentation: Creates a 2D vector from `self` with the given value of `y`.

glam::Vec3::abs.documentation: Returns a vector containing the absolute value of each element of `self`.

glam::Vec3::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs` is
 less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two vectors contain similar elements. It works best when
 comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used depends on
 the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::Vec3::angle_between.documentation:
Returns the angle (in radians) between two vectors in the range `[0, +]`.
 The inputs do not need to be unit vectors however they must be non-zero.

glam::Vec3::any_orthogonal_vector.documentation:
Returns some vector that is orthogonal to the given one.
 The input vector must be finite and non-zero.
 The output vector is not necessarily unit length. For that use
 [`Self::any_orthonormal_vector()`] instead.

glam::Vec3::any_orthonormal_vector.documentation:
Returns any unit vector that is orthogonal to the given one.
 The input vector must be unit length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::ceil.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the smallest integer greater than or equal to a number for
 each element of `self`.

glam::Vec3::clamp.documentation:
Component-wise clamping of values, similar to [`f32::clamp`].
 Each element in `min` must be less-or-equal to the corresponding element in `max`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::clamp_length.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min` and no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max`, or if either `min` or `max` is negative, when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::clamp_length_max.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `max` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::clamp_length_min.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::cmpeq.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `==` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words, this computes `[self.x == rhs.x, self.y == rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec3::cmpge.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x >= rhs.x, self.y >= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec3::cmpgt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x > rhs.x, self.y > rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec3::cmple.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x <= rhs.x, self.y <= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec3::cmplt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x < rhs.x, self.y < rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec3::cmpne.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `!=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x != rhs.x, self.y != rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec3::copysign.documentation: Returns a vector with signs of `rhs` and the magnitudes of `self`.

glam::Vec3::cross.documentation: Computes the cross product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::Vec3::distance.documentation: Computes the Euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::Vec3::distance_squared.documentation: Compute the squared euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::Vec3::div_euclid.documentation: Returns the element-wise quotient of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.

glam::Vec3::dot.documentation: Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::Vec3::dot_into_vec.documentation: Returns a vector where every component is the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::Vec3::element_product.documentation:
Returns the product of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x * self.y * ..`.

glam::Vec3::element_sum.documentation:
Returns the sum of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x + self.y + ..`.

glam::Vec3::exp.documentation:
Returns a vector containing `e^self` (the exponential function) for each element of
 `self`.

glam::Vec3::extend.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` and the given `w` value.

glam::Vec3::floor.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the largest integer less than or equal to a number for each
 element of `self`.

glam::Vec3::fract.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this differs from the GLSL implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::Vec3::fract_gl.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this differs from the Rust implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::Vec3::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector from an array.

glam::Vec3::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.  If any element is either
 `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::Vec3::is_finite_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_finite` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_finite(), y.is_finite(), ...]`.

glam::Vec3::is_nan_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_nan` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_nan(), y.is_nan(), ...]`.

glam::Vec3::is_negative_bitmask.documentation:
Returns a bitmask with the lowest 3 bits set to the sign bits from the elements of `self`.
 A negative element results in a `1` bit and a positive element in a `0` bit.  Element `x` goes
 into the first lowest bit, element `y` into the second, etc.
 An element is negative if it has a negative sign, including -0.0, NaNs with negative sign
 bit and negative infinity.

glam::Vec3::is_normalized.documentation:
Returns whether `self` is length `1.0` or not.
 Uses a precision threshold of approximately `1e-4`.

glam::Vec3::length_recip.documentation:
Computes `1.0 / length()`.
 For valid results, `self` must _not_ be of length zero.

glam::Vec3::length_squared.documentation:
Computes the squared length of `self`.
 This is faster than `length()` as it avoids a square root operation.

glam::Vec3::lerp.documentation:
Performs a linear interpolation between `self` and `rhs` based on the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s` is `1.0`, the result
 will be equal to `rhs`. When `s` is outside of range `[0, 1]`, the result is linearly
 extrapolated.

glam::Vec3::max.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the maximum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[max(self.x, rhs.x), max(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics for maxNum and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec3::max_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal maximum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `max(x, y, ..)`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec3::max_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first maximum element of `self`.

glam::Vec3::midpoint.documentation:
Calculates the midpoint between `self` and `rhs`.
 The midpoint is the average of, or halfway point between, two vectors.
 `a.midpoint(b)` should yield the same result as `a.lerp(b, 0.5)`
 while being slightly cheaper to compute.

glam::Vec3::min.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the minimum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[min(x, rhs.x), min(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics for minNum and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec3::min_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal minimum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `min(x, y, ..)`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec3::min_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first minimum element of `self`.

glam::Vec3::move_towards.documentation:
Moves towards `rhs` based on the value `d`.
 When `d` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `d` is equal to
 `self.distance(rhs)`, the result will be equal to `rhs`. Will not go past `rhs`.

glam::Vec3::mul_add.documentation:
Fused multiply-add. Computes `(self * a) + b` element-wise with only one rounding
 error, yielding a more accurate result than an unfused multiply-add.
 Using `mul_add` *may* be more performant than an unfused multiply-add if the target
 architecture has a dedicated fma CPU instruction. However, this is not always true,
 and will be heavily dependant on designing algorithms with specific target hardware in
 mind.

glam::Vec3::normalize.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0.
 For valid results, `self` must be finite and _not_ of length zero, nor very close to zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`] and [`Self::normalize_or_zero()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if the resulting normalized vector is not finite when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::normalize_or.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns a
 fallback value.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be the fallback value.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::Vec3::normalize_or_zero.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns zero.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::Vec3::powf.documentation: Returns a vector containing each element of `self` raised to the power of `n`.

glam::Vec3::project_onto.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is zero length when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::project_onto_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::recip.documentation: Returns a vector containing the reciprocal `1.0/n` of each element of `self`.

glam::Vec3::reflect.documentation:
Returns the reflection vector for a given incident vector `self` and surface normal
 `normal`.
 `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::refract.documentation:
Returns the refraction direction for a given incident vector `self`, surface normal
 `normal` and ratio of indices of refraction, `eta`. When total internal reflection occurs,
 a zero vector will be returned.
 `self` and `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::reject_from.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` has a length of zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::reject_from_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::rem_euclid.documentation:
Returns the element-wise remainder of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.
 [Euclidean division]: f32::rem_euclid

glam::Vec3::rotate_axis.documentation:
Rotates around `axis` by `angle` (in radians).
 The axis must be a unit vector.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `axis` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3::rotate_towards.documentation:
Rotates towards `rhs` up to `max_angle` (in radians).
 When `max_angle` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `max_angle` is equal to
 `self.angle_between(rhs)`, the result will be parallel to `rhs`. If `max_angle` is negative,
 rotates towards the exact opposite of `rhs`. Will not go past the target.

glam::Vec3::rotate_x.documentation: Rotates around the x axis by `angle` (in radians).

glam::Vec3::rotate_y.documentation: Rotates around the y axis by `angle` (in radians).

glam::Vec3::rotate_z.documentation: Rotates around the z axis by `angle` (in radians).

glam::Vec3::round.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the nearest integer to a number for each element of `self`.
 Round half-way cases away from 0.0.

glam::Vec3::select.documentation:
Creates a vector from the elements in `if_true` and `if_false`, selecting which to use
 for each element of `self`.
 A true element in the mask uses the corresponding element from `if_true`, and false
 uses the element from `if_false`.

glam::Vec3::signum.documentation:
Returns a vector with elements representing the sign of `self`.
 - `1.0` if the number is positive, `+0.0` or `INFINITY`
 - `-1.0` if the number is negative, `-0.0` or `NEG_INFINITY`
 - `NAN` if the number is `NAN`

glam::Vec3::slerp.documentation:
Performs a spherical linear interpolation between `self` and `rhs` based on the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s` is `1.0`, the result
 will be equal to `rhs`. When `s` is outside of range `[0, 1]`, the result is linearly
 extrapolated.

glam::Vec3::splat.documentation: Creates a vector with all elements set to `v`.

glam::Vec3::trunc.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the integer part each element of `self`. This means numbers are
 always truncated towards zero.

glam::Vec3::truncate.documentation:
Creates a 2D vector from the `x` and `y` elements of `self`, discarding `z`.
 Truncation may also be performed by using [`self.xy()`][crate::swizzles::Vec3Swizzles::xy()].

glam::Vec3::with_x.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `x`.

glam::Vec3::with_y.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `y`.

glam::Vec3::with_z.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `z`.

glam::Vec3A::abs.documentation: Returns a vector containing the absolute value of each element of `self`.

glam::Vec3A::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs` is

 This can be used to compare if two vectors contain similar elements. It works best when

 the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::Vec3A::angle_between.documentation:
Returns the angle (in radians) between two vectors in the range `[0, +]`.
 The inputs do not need to be unit vectors however they must be non-zero.

glam::Vec3A::any_orthogonal_vector.documentation:
Returns some vector that is orthogonal to the given one.
 The input vector must be finite and non-zero.
 The output vector is not necessarily unit length. For that use
 [`Self::any_orthonormal_vector()`] instead.

glam::Vec3A::any_orthonormal_vector.documentation:
Returns any unit vector that is orthogonal to the given one.
 The input vector must be unit length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::ceil.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the smallest integer greater than or equal to a number for
 each element of `self`.

 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on

 # Panics

glam::Vec3A::clamp_length_min.documentation:

glam::Vec3A::distance_squared.documentation: Compute the squared euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::Vec3A::dot.documentation: Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::Vec3A::element_sum.documentation:

glam::Vec3A::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector from an array.

glam::Vec3A::from_vec4.documentation:
Creates a [`Vec3A`] from the `x`, `y` and `z` elements of `self` discarding `w`.
 On architectures where SIMD is supported such as SSE2 on `x86_64` this conversion is a noop.

 mind.

glam::Vec3A::normalize.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0.
 For valid results, `self` must be finite and _not_ of length zero, nor very close to zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`] and [`Self::normalize_or_zero()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if the resulting normalized vector is not finite when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::normalize_or.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns a
 fallback value.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be the fallback value.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::Vec3A::normalize_or_zero.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns zero.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::Vec3A::powf.documentation: Returns a vector containing each element of `self` raised to the power of `n`.

glam::Vec3A::project_onto.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is zero length when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::project_onto_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::recip.documentation: Returns a vector containing the reciprocal `1.0/n` of each element of `self`.

glam::Vec3A::reflect.documentation:
Returns the reflection vector for a given incident vector `self` and surface normal
 `normal`.
 `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::refract.documentation:
Returns the refraction direction for a given incident vector `self`, surface normal
 `normal` and ratio of indices of refraction, `eta`. When total internal reflection occurs,
 a zero vector will be returned.
 `self` and `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::reject_from.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` has a length of zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::reject_from_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::rem_euclid.documentation:
Returns the element-wise remainder of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.
 [Euclidean division]: f32::rem_euclid

glam::Vec3A::rotate_axis.documentation:
Rotates around `axis` by `angle` (in radians).
 The axis must be a unit vector.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `axis` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec3A::rotate_towards.documentation:
Rotates towards `rhs` up to `max_angle` (in radians).
 When `max_angle` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `max_angle` is equal to
 `self.angle_between(rhs)`, the result will be parallel to `rhs`. If `max_angle` is negative,
 rotates towards the exact opposite of `rhs`. Will not go past the target.

glam::Vec3A::rotate_x.documentation: Rotates around the x axis by `angle` (in radians).

glam::Vec3A::rotate_y.documentation: Rotates around the y axis by `angle` (in radians).

glam::Vec3A::rotate_z.documentation: Rotates around the z axis by `angle` (in radians).

glam::Vec3A::round.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the nearest integer to a number for each element of `self`.
 Round half-way cases away from 0.0.

glam::Vec3A::select.documentation:
Creates a vector from the elements in `if_true` and `if_false`, selecting which to use
 for each element of `self`.
 A true element in the mask uses the corresponding element from `if_true`, and false
 uses the element from `if_false`.

glam::Vec3A::signum.documentation:
Returns a vector with elements representing the sign of `self`.
 - `1.0` if the number is positive, `+0.0` or `INFINITY`
 - `-1.0` if the number is negative, `-0.0` or `NEG_INFINITY`
 - `NAN` if the number is `NAN`

glam::Vec3A::slerp.documentation:
Performs a spherical linear interpolation between `self` and `rhs` based on the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s` is `1.0`, the result
 will be equal to `rhs`. When `s` is outside of range `[0, 1]`, the result is linearly
 extrapolated.

glam::Vec3A::splat.documentation: Creates a vector with all elements set to `v`.

glam::Vec3A::trunc.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the integer part each element of `self`. This means numbers are
 always truncated towards zero.

glam::Vec3A::truncate.documentation:
Creates a 2D vector from the `x` and `y` elements of `self`, discarding `z`.
 Truncation may also be performed by using [`self.xy()`][crate::swizzles::Vec3Swizzles::xy()].

glam::Vec3A::with_x.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `x`.

glam::Vec3A::with_y.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `y`.

glam::Vec3A::with_z.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `z`.

glam::Vec4::abs.documentation: Returns a vector containing the absolute value of each element of `self`.

glam::Vec4::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs` is
 less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two vectors contain similar elements. It works best when
 comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used depends on
 the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::Vec4::ceil.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the smallest integer greater than or equal to a number for
 each element of `self`.

glam::Vec4::clamp.documentation:
Component-wise clamping of values, similar to [`f32::clamp`].
 Each element in `min` must be less-or-equal to the corresponding element in `max`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::clamp_length.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min` and no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max`, or if either `min` or `max` is negative, when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::clamp_length_max.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `max` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::clamp_length_min.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::cmpeq.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `==` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words, this computes `[self.x == rhs.x, self.y == rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec4::cmpge.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x >= rhs.x, self.y >= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec4::cmpgt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x > rhs.x, self.y > rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec4::cmple.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x <= rhs.x, self.y <= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec4::cmplt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x < rhs.x, self.y < rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec4::cmpne.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `!=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x != rhs.x, self.y != rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::Vec4::copysign.documentation: Returns a vector with signs of `rhs` and the magnitudes of `self`.

glam::Vec4::distance.documentation: Computes the Euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::Vec4::distance_squared.documentation: Compute the squared euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::Vec4::div_euclid.documentation: Returns the element-wise quotient of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.

glam::Vec4::dot.documentation: Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::Vec4::dot_into_vec.documentation: Returns a vector where every component is the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::Vec4::element_product.documentation:
Returns the product of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x * self.y * ..`.

glam::Vec4::element_sum.documentation:
Returns the sum of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x + self.y + ..`.

glam::Vec4::exp.documentation:
Returns a vector containing `e^self` (the exponential function) for each element of
 `self`.

glam::Vec4::floor.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the largest integer less than or equal to a number for each
 element of `self`.

glam::Vec4::fract.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this differs from the GLSL implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::Vec4::fract_gl.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this differs from the Rust implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::Vec4::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector from an array.

glam::Vec4::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.  If any element is either
 `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::Vec4::is_finite_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_finite` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_finite(), y.is_finite(), ...]`.

glam::Vec4::is_nan_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_nan` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_nan(), y.is_nan(), ...]`.

glam::Vec4::is_negative_bitmask.documentation:
Returns a bitmask with the lowest 4 bits set to the sign bits from the elements of `self`.
 A negative element results in a `1` bit and a positive element in a `0` bit.  Element `x` goes
 into the first lowest bit, element `y` into the second, etc.
 An element is negative if it has a negative sign, including -0.0, NaNs with negative sign
 bit and negative infinity.

glam::Vec4::is_normalized.documentation:
Returns whether `self` is length `1.0` or not.
 Uses a precision threshold of approximately `1e-4`.

glam::Vec4::length_recip.documentation:
Computes `1.0 / length()`.
 For valid results, `self` must _not_ be of length zero.

glam::Vec4::length_squared.documentation:
Computes the squared length of `self`.
 This is faster than `length()` as it avoids a square root operation.

glam::Vec4::lerp.documentation:
Performs a linear interpolation between `self` and `rhs` based on the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s` is `1.0`, the result
 will be equal to `rhs`. When `s` is outside of range `[0, 1]`, the result is linearly
 extrapolated.

glam::Vec4::max.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the maximum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[max(self.x, rhs.x), max(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics for maxNum and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec4::max_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal maximum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `max(x, y, ..)`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec4::max_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first maximum element of `self`.

glam::Vec4::midpoint.documentation:
Calculates the midpoint between `self` and `rhs`.
 The midpoint is the average of, or halfway point between, two vectors.
 `a.midpoint(b)` should yield the same result as `a.lerp(b, 0.5)`
 while being slightly cheaper to compute.

glam::Vec4::min.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the minimum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[min(x, rhs.x), min(self.y, rhs.y), ..]`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics for minNum and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec4::min_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal minimum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `min(x, y, ..)`.
 NaN propogation does not follow IEEE 754-2008 semantics and may differ on
 different SIMD architectures.

glam::Vec4::min_position.documentation: Returns the index of the first minimum element of `self`.

glam::Vec4::move_towards.documentation:
Moves towards `rhs` based on the value `d`.
 When `d` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `d` is equal to
 `self.distance(rhs)`, the result will be equal to `rhs`. Will not go past `rhs`.

glam::Vec4::mul_add.documentation:
Fused multiply-add. Computes `(self * a) + b` element-wise with only one rounding
 error, yielding a more accurate result than an unfused multiply-add.
 Using `mul_add` *may* be more performant than an unfused multiply-add if the target
 architecture has a dedicated fma CPU instruction. However, this is not always true,
 and will be heavily dependant on designing algorithms with specific target hardware in
 mind.

glam::Vec4::normalize.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0.
 For valid results, `self` must be finite and _not_ of length zero, nor very close to zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`] and [`Self::normalize_or_zero()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if the resulting normalized vector is not finite when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::normalize_or.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns a
 fallback value.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be the fallback value.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::Vec4::normalize_or_zero.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns zero.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::Vec4::powf.documentation: Returns a vector containing each element of `self` raised to the power of `n`.

glam::Vec4::project_onto.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is zero length when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::project_onto_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::recip.documentation: Returns a vector containing the reciprocal `1.0/n` of each element of `self`.

glam::Vec4::reflect.documentation:
Returns the reflection vector for a given incident vector `self` and surface normal
 `normal`.
 `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::refract.documentation:
Returns the refraction direction for a given incident vector `self`, surface normal
 `normal` and ratio of indices of refraction, `eta`. When total internal reflection occurs,
 a zero vector will be returned.
 `self` and `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::reject_from.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` has a length of zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::reject_from_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Vec4::rem_euclid.documentation:
Returns the element-wise remainder of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.
 [Euclidean division]: f32::rem_euclid

glam::Vec4::round.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the nearest integer to a number for each element of `self`.
 Round half-way cases away from 0.0.

glam::Vec4::select.documentation:
Creates a vector from the elements in `if_true` and `if_false`, selecting which to use
 for each element of `self`.
 A true element in the mask uses the corresponding element from `if_true`, and false
 uses the element from `if_false`.

glam::Vec4::signum.documentation:
Returns a vector with elements representing the sign of `self`.
 - `1.0` if the number is positive, `+0.0` or `INFINITY`
 - `-1.0` if the number is negative, `-0.0` or `NEG_INFINITY`
 - `NAN` if the number is `NAN`

glam::Vec4::splat.documentation: Creates a vector with all elements set to `v`.

glam::Vec4::trunc.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the integer part each element of `self`. This means numbers are
 always truncated towards zero.

glam::Vec4::truncate.documentation:
Creates a 3D vector from the `x`, `y` and `z` elements of `self`, discarding `w`.
 Truncation to [`Vec3`] may also be performed by using [`self.xyz()`][crate::swizzles::Vec4Swizzles::xyz()].
 To truncate to [`Vec3A`] use [`Vec3A::from_vec4()`].

glam::Vec4::with_w.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `w`.

glam::Vec4::with_x.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `x`.

glam::Vec4::with_y.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `y`.

glam::Vec4::with_z.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `z`.

uuid::Uuid::get_node_id.documentation:
If the UUID is the correct version (v1, or v6) this will return the
 node value as a 6-byte array. For other versions this will return `None`.

uuid::Uuid::is_max.documentation: Tests if the UUID is max (all ones).

uuid::Uuid::is_nil.documentation: Tests if the UUID is nil (all zeros).

uuid::Uuid::max.documentation:
The 'max UUID' (all ones).
 The max UUID is a special form of UUID that is specified to have all
 128 bits set to one.
 # References
 * [Max UUID in RFC 9562](https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc9562.html#section-5.10)
 # Examples
 Basic usage:
 ```
 # use uuid::Uuid;
 let uuid = Uuid::max();
 assert_eq!(
     "ffffffff-ffff-ffff-ffff-ffffffffffff",
     uuid.hyphenated().to_string(),
 );
 ```

uuid::Uuid::new_v4.documentation:
Creates a random UUID.
 This uses the [`getrandom`] crate to utilise the operating system's RNG
 as the source of random numbers. If you'd like to use a custom
 generator, don't use this method: generate random bytes using your
 custom generator and pass them to the
 [`uuid::Builder::from_random_bytes`][from_random_bytes] function
 instead.
 Note that usage of this method requires the `v4` feature of this crate
 to be enabled.
 # Examples
 Basic usage:
 ```
 # use uuid::{Uuid, Version};
 let uuid = Uuid::new_v4();
 assert_eq!(Some(Version::Random), uuid.get_version());
 ```
 # References
 * [UUID Version 4 in RFC 9562](https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc9562.html#section-5.4)
 [`getrandom`]: https://crates.io/crates/getrandom
 [from_random_bytes]: struct.Builder.html#method.from_random_bytes

uuid::Uuid::nil.documentation:
The 'nil UUID' (all zeros).
 The nil UUID is a special form of UUID that is specified to have all
 128 bits set to zero.
 # References
 * [Nil UUID in RFC 9562](https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc9562.html#section-5.9)
 # Examples
 Basic usage:
 ```
 # use uuid::Uuid;
 let uuid = Uuid::nil();
 assert_eq!(
     "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000",
     uuid.hyphenated().to_string(),
 );
 ```
